I was super bored and decided to calculate exactly how much they'd make if they sold every ticket to the US show. Used some excel napkin math and an api call on the wrestlecon website to find out how many GA seats there are (300, about 70 of which are sold right now). If they sell everything, that's $40590 in ticket revenue.

Did some research and tried to get an estimated range for costs for running the event. Assuming Namba goes (and someone else covers Miyu, Maki, and Yuka's flights), that's about $14000 for return flights for everyone. If they have to pay for hotel rooms for everyone, which they probably don't, wrestlecon hotel costs $260 per night for a double room which is $4160 for everyone for 2 nights. If they have to pay for venue hire, which they almost definitely don't, globe website says it's $5400 for half day. So base costs ranging somewhere from $14000 to $23560.

They sell out they get ticket revenue of $40,590. Estimated costs ranging from $14,000 to $23,560. So rough guess of earnings from $17,030 to $39,190. And that's before merch etc.

Koda could probably afford to bring Pom over if it sells out, which it probably will, and still have decent money. Honestly Koda could afford to bring the whole roster over if they want and are willing to cut into their earnings.

Anyway I'm going to sleep after that total waste of time. Good night everyone.

This board just suffers from classic 4chan contrarianism. Many casuals, marks an "smarks" agree that the best moments in wrestling are those where the in ring work is the story. The drama is just additional context. Andre vs Hogan tells a story within the match. The classic David vs Goliath theme and the whole story is "will Hogan beat Andre?". Now there was a storyline behind that match, one in which Hogan and Andre used to be friends but Andre suddenly turned on Hogan to be the champion or some shit and tore his t shirt in half breaking their friendship leaving Hogan devastated. But that didn't matter. What mattered is that Hogan could body slam the massive behemoth of a man that Andre was to win the match. And that what people remember of wrestling. Not the "storyline" but the actual story in a match. We didn't care that Seth came out wearing Dusty's attire in the HIAC match against the code man. What actually mattered was that Cody was fighting with a torn pec and came out victorious in the end. Wrestling storytelling depends on the simulation of violence and competition, not in reality show drama.

Because it's scripted fights and not real contests. People watch sports for the idea that they are watching a legit contest between two opponents and even though it may be likely one wins over the other "you never know". Wrestling's scripted nature takes away that natural angle. The thing that makes pro wrestling potentially enjoyable is, ironically, using that scripted nature to manipulate people's expectations and have them suspend their belief, like a good TV show or movie will do, into forgetting it is scripted and enjoying the arc of the story instead.
